          Discussion
Conclusion
Demographics in this study were collected from seven churches and 65 participants, 69% women and 31% men. Average age was 55 years old. Average time in the church was 21 years. Average income was $79,872. More than 75% of households included 2 or more people.
Trust Brokers: Participants trust independent researchers, doctors and their pastor over government.
Credible Brokers: Participants view independent researchers as the most credible source to provide information on the risks and benefits of genetically modified foods.
In underrepresented communities, consumer skepticism persists despite new discoveries in science &amp; technology. Food safety concerns remain even though biotechnology is commonly used in food production. Mistrust in government is pervasive in marginalized communities. Scientists should anticipate that citizen engagement in science and technology may require inclusion strategies beyond science cafes, focus groups, and citizen juries. To be responsive to cultural circumstances, historical realities and social skepticism, scientists may have to go to church to create a meaningful dialogue with underrepresented groups.
