Abstract
Genetically engineered crops have been grown for more than 20 years, re- sulting in widespread albeit variable benefits for farmers and consumers. We review current, likely, and potential genetic engineering (GE) applica- tions for the development of disease-resistant crop cultivars. Gene editing, gene drives, and synthetic biology offer novel opportunities to control viral,
